 used gospel rap to navigate complicated social and spiritual realities and to transform the Southland's fractured terrains into musical Zions. Armed with beats, rhymes, and bibles, they journeyed through black Lutheran congregations, prison ministries, African churches, reggae dancehalls, hip hop clubs, Nation of Islam meetings, and Black Lives Matter marches. Zanfagna's fascinating ethnography provides a contemporary and unique view of black LA, offering a much-needed perspective on how music and religion intertwine in people's everyday experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRap (Music)xReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aRap (Music)zCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520968790?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968790zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520968790/original  a978-3-11-066755-4 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA